    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:7c24f549-9cd8-44d3-bc0a-1f017d48d3ef",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 74-year-old woman who appears thinner than her stated age, with a careful, deliberate way of moving and a faint pallor that is most noticeable around her lips and eyelids. Over the last several months she has developed increasing fatigue, intermittent crampy abdominal discomfort, reduced appetite, and a change in bowel habits with alternating constipation and narrower stools. She sometimes excuses herself during conversations because of abdominal urgency, and she has become quietly anxious about episodes of dark blood streaking and an unintentional weight loss that her family first noticed when her clothes began to hang loosely from her frame.\n\nShe lives with her husband in a small suburban home and has long been the center of family gatherings, known for gardening, knitting, and bringing homemade soups to neighbors. Recently, however, {patientName} has cut back on her church volunteer work and weekly walks with friends because she tires easily and feels embarrassed by bloating and unpredictable bowel movements. She is a retired elementary school teacher, organized and thoughtful, and still keeps a notebook of symptoms and appointments in her handbag.\n\nAt home, {patientName} tries to maintain independence, but ordinary tasks now take more effort. She eats smaller meals because larger ones worsen her abdominal discomfort, and she often rests in the afternoon. Her daughter has started accompanying her to clinic visits, noticing that {patientName} downplays symptoms unless asked directly. Despite this, she remains engaged, polite, and determined to understand her illness and treatment options.\n\nSocially, she has strong family support, though the diagnosis has unsettled her. She worries about becoming a burden and about the possibility of surgery or chemotherapy, yet she is motivated by a desire to attend her granddaughter’s upcoming graduation. She does not smoke, drinks alcohol only rarely, and has no history of illicit drug use. Her daily routine is quieter than before, shaped by fatigue, abdominal symptoms, and the emotional weight of a new cancer diagnosis."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:0e20fcb8-4297-4a22-8953-0a73ccc03862",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has a recent history of progressively worsening fatigue, decreased exercise tolerance, intermittent lower abdominal cramping, and several months of altered bowel habits. She reports unintentional weight loss and occasional blood mixed with stool. Her primary care evaluation noted pallor and concern for anemia, leading to further gastrointestinal workup and eventual diagnosis of colon malignancy. She has no prior history of inflammatory bowel disease and no known hereditary cancer syndrome, though age is a major risk factor.\n\nHer past medical history includes hypertension and chronic constipation, both previously managed in the outpatient setting. She has not had prior cancer treatment before this diagnosis. She was hospitalized once in the past few years for dehydration related to a viral gastroenteritis but otherwise has had relatively stable health for her age. Functionally, she remains independent in basic activities of daily living but now needs more rest because of fatigue.\n\nLifestyle factors are overall favorable: {patientName} is a lifelong nonsmoker, rarely drinks alcohol, and was previously moderately active through walking and gardening. Her diet has historically been mixed, though recently reduced because of poor appetite and abdominal discomfort. She has strong support from her husband and adult daughter, both of whom help with transportation, meals, and follow-up appointments."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
